DMCI, Energy, Holcim, SM Prime: Philippines Stocks Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-07-14T00:37:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-14/dmci-energy-holcim-sm-prime-philippines-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 1.2 percent to
4,404.  Infrastructure-related companies: Philippine Finance
Secretary Cesar Purisima said the government will offer for
bidding 10 infrastructure projects this year, reiterating an
earlier plan.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)  , which owns the
company that operates the nation’s longest toll road, increased
0.8 percent to 3.62 pesos.  Holcim Philippines Inc. (HLCM)  ,
the nation’s biggest cement producer, was unchanged at 11.02
pesos.  DMCI Holdings Inc. (DMC)  , the nation’s largest
construction company, rose 0.5 percent to 43.15 pesos.  Energy Development Corp. (EDC)  : The  Philippines ’ largest
geothermal company expects so-called reported income for 2011 to
drop “significantly” due to lower electricity prices and
foregone revenue from a plant that’s being repaired, President
Richard Tantoco said.  The company expects to increase its capacity by 130
megawatts in the fourth quarter, Chief Financial Officer Nestor
Vasay said in a report given out to shareholders. Recent
acquisitions and rehabilitation at some of its facilities will
“deliver meaningful” revenues starting early next year, Vasay
said. The stock climbed 0.9 percent to 6.94 pesos.  First Philippine Holdings Corp. (FPH)  : The company
bought back 300,000 shares at 60.855 pesos each in the open
market, according to a stock exchange filing. The stock fell 0.1
percent to 60.85 pesos.  Pacific Online Systems Corp. (LOTO)  : The company that
leases terminals for the online lottery operated by the
Philippine government bought back 240,000 shares at 20.55 pesos
each, a stock exchange filing showed. The stock advanced 1.5
percent to 21 pesos.  SM Prime Holdings Inc. (SMPH)  : The largest Philippine
shopping mall operator has offered “no less than” 2 billion
pesos ($46.5 million) to develop a 7.7 hectare, government
property in Negros Occidental, Chief Financial Officer Jeffrey
Lim said. The stock increased 1.6 percent to 11.68 pesos.  Vista Land & Lifescapes Inc. (VLL)  : The developer bought
back 250,000 shares at 3.17 pesos each in the open market, a
stock exchange filing showed. The stock increased 0.6 percent to
3.18 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
